## Policy and Regulatory Measures

Government policies are essential to enforce and incentivize large-scale reductions in air pollution.

### Transportation Sector Policies

Transportation is the largest contributor to air pollution in urban areas. Effective policies include:

| Policy Type       | Description                                                                                  | Examples and Impact                                                                                              |
|-------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Incentive Policies | Subsidies for public transport, free transit programs to reduce private car use               | Encourages modal shift, reduces vehicle miles traveled ([Springer, 2021](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40201-021-00744-4)) |
| Supportive Policies| Subsidies for cleaner household fuels, EV adoption incentives                                | Facilitates transition to low-emission technologies                                                           |
| Punitive Policies  | Congestion charges, tolls for high-polluting vehicles                                       | Discourages use of polluting vehicles, reduces urban traffic and emissions ([Springer, 2021](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40201-021-00744-4)) |
| Emission Standards | Stricter vehicle emission limits, mandatory vehicle inspections and maintenance              | Proven to reduce NOx, PM, and VOC emissions ([Climatetracker, 2018](https://climatetracker.org/25-solutions-to-air-pollution/)) |

Additional measures include traffic management, low emission zones, and promotion of electric public transport ([Springer, 2021](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40201-021-00744-4)).

### Energy and Industrial Policies

- **Fuel Transition:** Phasing out solid fuels like coal in favor of cleaner energy sources such as natural gas, electricity, and renewables reduces SO2, NOx, and PM emissions ([Springer, 2021](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40201-021-00744-4)).
- **Industrial Emission Controls:** Implementing advanced emission standards and pollution control technologies in industries such as steel, cement, and chemical manufacturing lowers toxic emissions ([Climatetracker, 2018](https://climatetracker.org/25-solutions-to-air-pollution/)).
- **Waste Management Regulations:** Banning open burning of residential and agricultural waste, promoting composting and centralized waste treatment reduce particulate and toxic emissions ([Climatetracker, 2018](https://climatetracker.org/25-solutions-to-air-pollution/)).

### National Clean Air Programs

Examples include Indiaâ€™s National Clean Air Programme (NCAP), targeting a 20-30% reduction in PM10 and PM2.5 concentrations by 2024 in 102 non-attainment cities, demonstrating the effectiveness of coordinated action plans ([Green Clean Guide, 2019](https://greencleanguide.com/india-various-initiatives-or-mitigation-of-air-pollution/)).

### Legislative Actions

- **Clean Air Acts:** Laws that restrict emissions from vehicles, industries, and domestic fuels have historically improved air quality ([UK Government, 2019](https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-clean-air-strategy-to-be-launched-by-environment-secretary-michael-gove)).
- **Ammonia Emission Controls:** Targeting agricultural sources responsible for 88% of ammonia emissions through infrastructure investments ([UK Government, 2019](https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-clean-air-strategy-to-be-launched-by-environment-secretary-michael-gove)).

